32:52.224 --> 32:53.866
Yeah, she probably five or six now.

32:53.907 --> 32:54.447
Five or six?

32:54.468 --> 32:55.890
Yeah, it's been a couple of years.

32:56.162 --> 32:57.404
kids do age, don't they?

32:57.544 --> 32:57.905
They do.

32:58.245 --> 33:01.811
This is just three or four when you were there two and a half years ago.

33:02.212 --> 33:08.423
And then so yeah, so they've got a bunch of kids that are in that like high school, early college range.

33:08.443 --> 33:12.850
And so I know for his family a big thing about trips that we teach all of our teams is

33:13.026 --> 33:28.082
You go there to minister to three groups of people, you minister to your actual team, then you minister to the pastor and the church that you're a part of, their family, that organization, and then you minister to the people broadly, in a sense.

33:28.103 --> 33:39.455
And so like going to Japan specifically, that's a big part of that is to encourage Fabio and his family, because it is a 1%, I guess now 2%, or almost 2%.

33:39.535 --> 33:42.258
Yeah, it seems like it's growing.

33:42.850 --> 33:44.152
um, Christian nation.

33:44.192 --> 33:56.672
And so you're, you're talking about a place where even though Christianity is not outlawed in any type of way, it's still such a cultural minority that you could be a Christian in Japan and have a really hard time finding other Christians.

33:57.293 --> 34:01.239
Like it's not like here you're like, you might feel like you're the only one at work that's a Christian.

34:01.680 --> 34:03.843
And then you pull out your Bible and somebody's like, Oh, me too.

34:04.083 --> 34:07.048
And it's like, there's others in Japan, most likely not.

34:07.909 --> 34:10.834
Um, and so you're there to encourage them when life gets lonely.

34:11.170 --> 34:19.058
But a big part of their ministry is actually using English to reach people.

34:19.118 --> 34:30.550
So they do a lot of events and things around teaching English or creating opportunities for English conversations, because a lot of people will study English, but they need somewhere to practice.

34:31.431 --> 34:36.035
And being able to practice with an actual native English speaker is huge.

34:36.095 --> 34:38.578
That's a value that a lot of people don't get.

34:38.786 --> 34:48.137
Because like when you're taking English in a Japanese school, most likely you're learning from somebody who speaks English as a second or third or fourth language.

34:48.538 --> 34:50.781
And so they're speaking with a Japanese accent or something.

34:50.801 --> 34:55.527
So when you get a chance to actually talk with a native speaker, it makes a huge impact.

34:55.627 --> 35:03.116
And so they capitalize on that, which means because they're using English, it's also they're hitting a lot of younger people.

35:03.757 --> 35:08.082
So they're in college campuses and they're reaching a lot of just

35:08.194 --> 35:11.836
in that young working professional and high school and college kids.

35:12.822 --> 35:15.378
And so bringing a team full of 80 year olds.

35:15.842 --> 35:18.004
It's hard to connect there.

35:18.525 --> 35:21.367
But if you bring a team of 20-year-olds, it's perfect.

35:21.387 --> 35:24.891
And the nature of it is a whole lot of walking and moving around.

35:24.911 --> 35:26.352
It's a very physical trip.

35:26.553 --> 35:30.697
Yeah, we stay on the third floor of the church and there's no elevators.

35:30.817 --> 35:34.060
